REPORT 3 — AI Scribe Patient Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA)
Title: Privacy Impact Assessment for AI Clinical Scribe Deployment in Remote Primary Care Clinic
Region: North America
Industry: Healthcare (Telemedicine)
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
A remote primary care clinic piloted an AI clinical scribe to automate documentation during telehealth visits. During the pilot, the AI vendor temporarily stored audio transcripts in a U.S.-based cloud region despite the clinic’s Canadian patient base.

This triggered concerns about:

Data residency

Unauthorized access

AI hallucination risks

Clinician over‑reliance on generated notes

This Privacy Impact Assessment evaluates the privacy, security, and behavioral risks associated with the AI scribe and maps them to HIPAA Security Rule and NIST CSF 2.0 controls.

2. Background
The clinic uses telehealth exclusively and handles sensitive patient data, including:

Mental health disclosures

Medication history

Diagnostic impressions

Family medical history

The AI scribe listens to patient encounters, generates structured notes, and syncs them to the EHR.

A routine vendor review revealed that audio files were temporarily cached in a region outside the clinic’s approved data residency zone.

Your role:

Conduct a Privacy Impact Assessment

Identify risks

Map controls

Recommend mitigations

3. Scope
This PIA covers:

Data collection, processing, storage, and deletion

Vendor data handling practices

AI model behavior risks

Human factors (clinician reliance, confirmation bias)

HIPAA and NIST CSF 2.0 alignment

4. Data Flow Overview
Data Collected
Audio of patient encounters

Transcripts

Summaries and structured notes

Metadata (timestamps, clinician ID, encounter type)

Processing Steps
Audio captured during telehealth session

Sent to AI vendor for transcription

AI model generates SOAP note

Clinician reviews and approves

Final note stored in EHR

Vendor deletes cached data (per policy)

Identified Issue
Vendor cached audio in a U.S. region for up to 72 hours, violating the clinic’s data residency requirement.

5. Risk Assessment
Risk 1 — Data Residency Non‑Compliance
Description:  
Audio files stored outside approved region.

HIPAA Mapping:

§164.308(a)(1) — Security Management Process

§164.312(e)(1) — Transmission Security

Impact:  
Regulatory exposure, cross‑border data transfer risk.

Likelihood: Medium
Severity: High

Risk 2 — Unauthorized Access to Cached Audio
Description:  
Temporary storage increases attack surface.

HIPAA Mapping:

§164.312(a)(1) — Access Control

§164.312(b) — Audit Controls

Impact:  
Potential ePHI exposure.

Likelihood: Medium
Severity: High

Risk 3 — AI Hallucination in Clinical Notes
Description:  
AI generated incorrect medication dosages in 3 of 50 pilot encounters.

HIPAA Mapping:

§164.308(a)(1)(ii)(B) — Risk Management

§164.312(c)(1) — Integrity Controls

Impact:  
Patient safety risk, inaccurate medical record.

Likelihood: Medium
Severity: High

Risk 4 — Clinician Over‑Reliance (Psychology Lens)
Description:  
Clinicians accepted AI‑generated notes without verifying accuracy.

Behavioral Factors:

Automation bias

Cognitive offloading

Time pressure

Impact:  
Incorrect diagnoses or treatment plans.

Likelihood: High
Severity: Medium

6. Controls Evaluation
Existing Controls
Vendor BAA in place

TLS enforced for all transmissions

Clinician review required before note finalization

Audit logs enabled in EHR

Missing or Weak Controls
No residency enforcement in vendor contract

No automated deletion verification

No hallucination detection workflow

No training on AI cognitive bias

7. Recommendations
Governance Controls
Update BAA to include explicit residency clauses

Require vendor to provide data deletion certificates

Implement quarterly vendor compliance audits

Technical Controls
Enforce region‑locked storage

Enable anomaly detection for AI‑generated notes

Require multi‑factor authentication for vendor dashboard

Human Behavior Controls
Train clinicians on automation bias

Require mandatory double‑check for medications and diagnoses

Add “AI Confidence Score” to notes to prompt review

8. Residual Risk
After implementing recommended controls:

Data Residency Risk: Low

Unauthorized Access Risk: Low

Hallucination Risk: Medium (AI limitation)

Over‑Reliance Risk: Medium (human factor)

